  "text": "The 'overflow' reset reason error occurs when Envoy's connection pool exhausts resource limits configured via circuit breakers. Here's the complete trace:\n\n## 1. Reset Reason Definition\nThe 'overflow' string is defined in `source/common/http/utility.cc` (line 1031) in the `Utility::resetReasonToString()` function, which converts `Http::StreamResetReason::Overflow` to the string \"overflow\". The enum `StreamResetReason::Overflow` is declared in `envoy/http/stream_reset_handler.h` (line 33).\n\n## 2. Connection Pool Overflow Triggers\nTwo scenarios trigger the `PoolFailureReason::Overflow` in `source/common/conn_pool/conn_pool_base.cc`:\n\n**Scenario A (line 175-178):** Max active requests exceeded\n- When `enforceMaxRequests()` returns true and `requests().canCreate()` returns false, indicating the max_requests circuit breaker limit is reached\n- Logs: \"max streams overflow\"\n- Increments: `upstream_rq_pending_overflow_` stat\n\n**Scenario B (line 282-286):** Max pending requests exceeded  \n- When `pendingRequests().canCreate()` returns false, indicating the max_pending_requests circuit breaker limit is reached\n- Logs: \"max pending streams overflow\"\n- This is checked before creating new connections for pending streams\n\n## 3. Error Propagation Chain\n1. Connection pool detects overflow → calls `onPoolFailure()` with `PoolFailureReason::Overflow`\n2. `source/common/router/upstream_request.cc` (line 567-579): `UpstreamRequest::onPoolFailure()` maps `ConnectionPool::PoolFailureReason::Overflow` to `Http::StreamResetReason::Overflow`\n3. Stream is reset with this reason\n4. `Utility::resetReasonToString()` converts it to \"overflow\" for logging\n\n## 4. Resource Management\nThe circuit breaker limits are enforced by `ResourceManagerImpl` in `source/common/upstream/resource_manager_impl.h`, which manages:\n- `connections_`: max concurrent connections (ManagedResourceImpl using canCreate())\n- `pending_requests_`: max pending requests (ManagedResourceImpl using canCreate())\n- `requests_`: max active requests (ManagedResourceImpl using canCreate())\n- `connection_pools_`: max connection pools per cluster\n\nWhen `canCreate()` returns false for any resource, new streams/connections are rejected.\n\n## 5. Configuration Protobufs\nCircuit breaker limits are configured in:\n- `envoy/config/cluster/v3/circuit_breaker.proto`: Current v3 API\n  - `CircuitBreakers.Thresholds.max_connections` (field 2): Default 1024\n  - `CircuitBreakers.Thresholds.max_pending_requests` (field 3): Default 1024\n  - `CircuitBreakers.Thresholds.max_requests` (field 4): Default 1024\n- `envoy/api/v2/cluster/circuit_breaker.proto`: Deprecated v2 API (same structure)\n\nEach Thresholds message applies to a specific `RoutingPriority`, allowing per-priority configuration.\n\n## HTTP Connection Pool Implementations\nThe circuit breaker checks happen in the base connection pool classes:\n- `source/common/http/conn_pool_base.h/cc`: Base HTTP connection pool that inherits from `ConnPoolImplBase`\n- This base class is inherited by protocol-specific implementations:\n  - HTTP/1: `source/common/http/http1/conn_pool.h/cc`\n  - HTTP/2: `source/common/http/http2/conn_pool.h/cc`\n  - HTTP/3: `source/common/http/http3/conn_pool.h/cc`\n\nWhen a stream request cannot be satisfied due to resource exhaustion, the overflow failure is propagated through the call chain above."
}

